{:metadata {:description [{"text" "<p>This 2,3-bisphosphoglycerate-independent phosphoglycerate mutase (iPGAM) is a metalloenzyme found particularly in eubacteria and higher plants. It is distantly related to archaeal iPGAM ([interpro:IPR004456]) and distinct from the unrelated cofactor-dependent PGAM. Activity has been demonstrated for proteins from a variety of organisms, including Pseudomonas syringae pv. tomato [[cite:PUB00014416]], Bacillus subtilis [[cite:PUB00014367]], Bacillus stearothermophilus [[cite:PUB00014404]], maize [[cite:PUB00002717]], castor bean [[cite:PUB00014371]], and Trypanosoma brucei [[cite:PUB00014401]]. The structure of the B. stearothermophilus enzyme has two domains [[cite:PUB00014365]]. Residues 1-76 and 311-511 form the phosphatase domain, containing the active site residue and two metal-binding sites. This domain is similar to alkaline phosphatase and arylsulphatase, which are members of the SCOP alkaline phosphatase-like superfamily, but there is meagre sequence similarity outside of the metal-binding segments. Residues 77-310 form the phosphotransferase domain, which is poorly conserved (or perhaps unrelated) in the archaeal enzymes.</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false}], :is-reviewed-llm false, :representative-structure {"accession" "1o98", "name" "1.4A CRYSTAL STRUCTURE OF PHOSPHOGLYCERATE MUTASE FROM BACILLUS STEAROTHERMOPHILUS COMPLEXED WITH 2-PHOSPHOGLYCERATE"}, :overlaps-with [{"accession" "IPR017850", "name" "Alkaline-phosphatase-like, core domain superfamily", "type" "homologous_superfamily"} {"accession" "IPR036646", "name" "BPG-independent phosphoglycerate mutase, domain B superfamily", "type" "homologous_superfamily"}], :member-databases {"cdd" {"cd16010" "2 3 bisphosphoglycerate independent phosphoglycerate mutase iPGM"}, "panther" {"PTHR31637" "2,3-BISPHOSPHOGLYCERATE-INDEPENDENT PHOSPHOGLYCERATE MUTASE"}, "hamap" {"MF_01038" "2,3-bisphosphoglycerate-independent phosphoglycerate mutase [gpmI]"}, "pirsf" 